{Can you survive without castling against the Wolrd Champion?} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Qe2 (6. Nbd2 Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 (8.
Nf1) 8... Bg6 9. Nxe5 Qd4) 6... Qe7 7. Nbd2 Bg4 8. h3 Bh5 9. a3 (9. Nf1 {With
the idea Nf1-g3. But Qe2 would be a waste in that case of ...Bxf3.}) (9. g4)
9... Nd7 (9... a5 {black won't be able to castle queenside}) 10. b4 Bd6 (10...
Bd4 11. Rb1 Bc3 12. O-O Bxd2 13. Bxd2 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 $14) 11. Nc4 f6 12. Ne3 {
Now the point of a3-b4 is obvious because if the bishop was on c5 he had
chopped ...Bxe3} a5 13. Nf5 Qf8 (13... Qf7 14. Rb1 axb4 15. axb4 {The a file
won't be too useful for black}) 14. bxa5 (14. Nxd6+ {This would be a huge a
strategical concession}) 14... Rxa5 15. O-O {Now is all about time.} Qf7 16. a4
Nc5 (16... O-O 17. Bh6 $3 gxh6 18. Nxh6+) 17. Qe1 $1 {Attacking Ra5 and
freeing the Nf3} b6 (17... Rxa4 18. Rxa4 Nxa4 19. Qa5 Nb6 20. Nxd6+) 18. Nd2
Rxa4 19. Nc4 $1 Bf8 (19... Rxa1 20. Ncxd6+ cxd6 21. Nxd6+) (19... Kd7 20. Rxa4
Nxa4 21. Ncxd6 cxd6 22. Qb4) (19... Be7 20. Be3 Rxa1 (20... Kd7 21. Rxa4 (21.
Nxb6+) 21... Nxa4 22. f4) (20... O-O 21. Bh6 (21. Nxe7+ Qxe7 22. Bxc5 {wins a
piece})) 21. Qxa1 O-O 22. Bh6) 20. Be3 Kd7 (20... Rxa1 21. Qxa1) 21. Qc3 {
Threatening 22.Nxb6+ cxb6 23.Bxc5 Rxa1 24.Rxa1 winning!} Nxe4 (21... Rxc4 22.
dxc4 Nxe4 23. Qd3+ Nd6 24. g4 Bg6 25. Rfd1 $16 {The rook on h8 and the bishop
f8 do not play.}) 22. Nxb6+ $1 (22. dxe4 Qxc4) 22... cxb6 23. dxe4 Qc4 (23...
Rxa1 24. Rxa1) 24. Qd2+ Kc7 25. g4 Bg6 26. Rfd1 {So I guess the lesson from
this game is you should castle pretty early on. And sometimes delaying
development in order to attain some positional goals can be profitable. But
very often it is very risky. And most of all it forces you to play so
precisely later on that it is just something that a lot of people want to do.
You can see from this game that Wesley So is a very good player. So it feels
like he can't break these rules from time to time because he is so good that
he knows when to break them and when not to break them. Except sometimes he
even he gets it wrong like in this game he couldn't really balance development
and postional things. Actually I'm pretty proud of this game for playing very
energetically, and you could say I wasn't too brave in this game. I didn't
have to sacrifice so much material. But then again you don't always have to be.
Sometimes it is enough to be able to sacrifice one pawn or to sacrifice some
positional considerations for more time gains that you have to make. If you
are brave to do it. And you follow it up well playing energetically taking
your chances of exploiting your tactical opportunities that you have I think
you can do very well.} 1-0


