{A Closed Sicilian win à la Spassky} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. g3 (3. d4 cxd4 4.
Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2) 3... Nc6 4. Bg2 g6 5. d3 Bg7 6. Be3 (6. f4) 6... e5 7. Nh3 {
I was inspired by games of Spassky on putting the knight on h3} Nge7 8. f4 Nd4
(8... O-O 9. f5 (9. O-O) 9... gxf5 10. Qh5) 9. O-O O-O 10. Qd2 {I want to keep
the pieces on the board Nd1 and c3} Bd7 {With the idea of ...Qc8. It doesnt\'t
make a lot of sense} (10... f6 {Trying to solidify the center and ...Be6}) 11.
Nd1 Qc8 12. Ndf2 Ndc6 13. c3 b5 $6 (13... b6 14. fxe5 (14. Ng5) (14. f5 gxf5
15. Bh6 f6) 14... dxe5 {Keeping more central control} 15. Ng5 {provoking 15...
f6 and 16.Nf3}) 14. fxe5 Nxe5 15. Bh6 (15. d4 Nc4) 15... N7c6 {It is really
hard to find a plan for black.} 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Nf4 Qd8 18. Rad1 Rc8 19. Qe2
h5 $6 20. d4 cxd4 21. cxd4 Ng4 22. h3 Nxf2 23. Qxf2 {With ideas of Nd5 and Qf4}
Ne7 24. Rd3 b4 25. Rf3 Qe8 (25... Bb5 26. Nxh5+ (26. Re1) 26... gxh5 27. Rxf7+
Rxf7 28. Qxf7+ Kh6 (28... Kh8 29. Qxh5+) 29. Rf6+) 26. g4 $1 (26. d5 a5 27. Qb6
{This was also good. But I did not want to change my plan of central control
and possible attack on the kingside}) 26... hxg4 27. hxg4 {With the idea Qh4}
Bb5 (27... Bxg4 28. Rg3 Qd7 29. Bh3 $1) 28. Re1 Qd8 29. g5 Qb6 (29... Nc6 30.
Rg3 {With the idea Nd5} Qb6 31. Rd1 {And I retain all of the advantafes of my
position}) 30. Bh3 Rcd8 31. Be6 $1 Be8 (31... fxe6 32. Nxe6+) 32. Nd5 Nxd5 33.
Bxd5 {Black has no counterplay at all!!!! White threatens Rf1, or Kg2 & Rh1 or
Rh3 & Qh4.} 1-0



